
DNS (Domain Name System)
🎯 Objective

Learn what DNS is, why it is needed, how it works, understand DNS records, and practice common Linux commands used for DNS troubleshooting.

📖 What is DNS?

DNS (Domain Name System) is the phonebook of the Internet.

Humans remember domain names like:

www.google.com

Computers communicate using IP addresses like:

142.250.183.206

DNS translates the domain name into its corresponding IP address.

Why Do We Need DNS?

Without DNS, you would have to remember IP addresses for every website.

For example:

Instead of typing:

https://www.google.com

you would need to remember something like:

142.250.183.206

DNS makes the Internet easier to use by converting human-readable names into machine-readable IP addresses.

