Types of DNS Servers
1. Recursive Resolver
Receives the DNS query from the client.
Finds the required IP address.
2. Root Name Server
Directs the request to the correct Top-Level Domain (TLD) server.
3. TLD Server
Handles domains like:
.com
.org
.in
.net
4. Authoritative Name Server

Returns the final IP address of the requested domain.


Common DNS Record Types

| Record | Purpose                                       |
| ------ | --------------------------------------------- |
| A      | Maps a domain name to an IPv4 address         |
| AAAA   | Maps a domain name to an IPv6 address         |
| CNAME  | Creates an alias for another domain           |
| MX     | Specifies the mail server                     |
| NS     | Specifies the authoritative name server       |
| TXT    | Stores verification or other text information |
| PTR    | Reverse DNS lookup (IP → Domain)              |


Linux Commands
Check DNS Resolution
nslookup google.com

Display DNS Information (if dig is installed)
dig google.com

Display Host Information
host google.com

Test Connectivity
ping google.com

View Configured DNS Servers
cat /etc/resolv.conf


Advantages of DNS
Easy to remember domain names.
Fast translation of names to IP addresses.
Supports load balancing.
Highly scalable.
Distributed and fault tolerant.
Limitations
If a DNS server fails, websites may become unreachable by name.
Incorrect DNS configuration can prevent access to services.
Can be targeted by attacks such as DNS spoofing or cache poisoning.


